WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.880
Alright, so I want to talk today about the next generation of R Markdown, which is a

00:00:13.880 --> 00:00:18.520
package that has been available for a couple of years now, but over the past couple of

00:00:18.520 --> 00:00:22.440
months we've really overhauled it and added a lot of new interesting features.

00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:27.040
So before we dig in too deep, I'll just introduce you to Markdown if you're not familiar.

00:00:27.040 --> 00:00:32.919
So Markdown, they define it as a plain text formatting syntax, but the idea is that you're

00:00:32.919 --> 00:00:37.259
really just typing in plain text and then it's going to render to more complex formats.

00:00:37.259 --> 00:00:44.320
So if you've ever created a txt file, then you've already done half the battle.

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:51.639
Really the format allows you to focus on, really more primarily just on creating the

00:00:51.639 --> 00:00:56.680
content that you want to write without having to worry about the formatting and the markup

00:00:56.680 --> 00:00:58.799
and things like that.

00:00:58.799 --> 00:01:03.080
But what's great about this is that you can just write your text, just focus on the content,

00:01:03.080 --> 00:01:07.680
and then later render that to HTML or PDF or some other format.

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:13.760
And so R Markdown is a package that allows you to do this from within R.

00:01:13.760 --> 00:01:19.360
So Markdown, just as an example, here are a few things that, just Markdown conventions.

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:24.160
So again, you're just typing normal text primarily most of the time, but if you want to do different

00:01:24.160 --> 00:01:25.839
levels of headers, you can do those.

00:01:25.839 --> 00:01:27.599
You can create bold things.

00:01:27.599 --> 00:01:29.680
You can create hyperlinks or lists or tables.

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:35.519
So the power is there if you do want to create these more complex formats, but typically

00:01:35.519 --> 00:01:39.760
it allows you just to focus on the content rather than needing to worry about making

00:01:39.760 --> 00:01:42.760
sure that everything's styled correctly and flowing correctly.

00:01:42.760 --> 00:01:52.199
All right, so R Markdown then is, it's kind of a package in the realm of literate programming.

00:01:52.199 --> 00:02:00.199
And the idea is that rather than embedding comments in a string of code that you have,

00:02:00.199 --> 00:02:04.000
that instead you would actually embed the code within the document that you're writing.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.320
So you can write kind of this narrative and sort of create this prose that describes the

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:13.199
analysis that you're doing, and then within that just embed chunks of R code.

00:02:13.199 --> 00:02:17.360
And obviously there are a variety of different ways that you can leverage the tool, but that's

00:02:17.360 --> 00:02:21.479
one of the more popular ones we see in terms of reproducible research and literate programming.

00:02:21.759 --> 00:02:25.279
But the idea is that you're going to render the textual output and the graphical output

00:02:25.279 --> 00:02:29.279
and anything else that R is creating just in line within your document.

00:02:29.279 --> 00:02:30.839
So this is an example here.

00:02:30.839 --> 00:02:34.639
So on the left you can see that this would be the input format.

00:02:34.639 --> 00:02:38.839
So there's this convention of three backticks, and then you specify that using the R language.

00:02:38.839 --> 00:02:42.360
And then in here you just write any R code that you want, and then you close that with

00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:44.039
three more backticks.

00:02:44.039 --> 00:02:46.279
And what that would render is what you see on the right here.

00:02:46.279 --> 00:02:50.520
So you would see that you have your input commands, and you can see those just match

00:02:50.559 --> 00:02:53.479
the first two lines of your input.

00:02:53.479 --> 00:02:55.440
And then any output that's textual here.

00:02:55.440 --> 00:02:59.479
So when you run length X, you get the output here, which is 100.

00:02:59.479 --> 00:03:04.919
And then afterwards we do histX to produce the histogram, and you can see as well that

00:03:04.919 --> 00:03:11.839
the image is just going to be embedded directly in your document or your slideshow or whatever

00:03:11.839 --> 00:03:12.839
it is you're creating.

00:03:12.839 --> 00:03:19.119
So this is a really easy way for you to work with your R analysis in a format that you

00:03:19.119 --> 00:03:24.559
want to share with someone who may not be comfortable running your R code themselves.

00:03:24.559 --> 00:03:29.119
So I had mentioned that the R Markdown package has actually been around for a while.

00:03:29.119 --> 00:03:35.160
And so this was primarily the old workflow, is that you had R Markdown, that would render

00:03:35.160 --> 00:03:39.520
to Markdown, and then we used a tool called Sundown to create HTML, and you could actually

00:03:39.520 --> 00:03:45.399
create LaTeX and PDF out of this as well, but it was kind of a more simplified pipeline.

00:03:45.399 --> 00:03:48.460
So this is just an example R Markdown file I have.

00:03:48.460 --> 00:03:52.419
You can see, again, most of it's just text, like I had explained before.

00:03:52.419 --> 00:03:54.580
We have some special formatting.

00:03:54.580 --> 00:03:57.500
We have a couple of R chunks here.

00:03:57.500 --> 00:04:00.539
And then we're doing actually a couple more advanced features, but I won't go into the

00:04:00.539 --> 00:04:01.539
syntax of these.

00:04:01.539 --> 00:04:08.059
But just so that you can see that they are possible here, you can do LaTeX style equations,

00:04:08.059 --> 00:04:11.460
you can do footnotes, you can do all sorts of things like that.

00:04:11.460 --> 00:04:15.699
But again, primarily the focus is just on creating prose and embedding your R code within

00:04:15.699 --> 00:04:16.700
that.

00:04:16.940 --> 00:04:22.700
So what I'm going to do is I'm going to knit that document to HTML, and you can see what

00:04:22.700 --> 00:04:24.500
that's going to produce.

00:04:24.500 --> 00:04:29.700
So this is an HTML file that happens to be shown in this RStudio viewer, but we could

00:04:29.700 --> 00:04:33.700
open this up in an external browser, we could share it, send it via email, whatever we want

00:04:33.700 --> 00:04:34.700
to do.

00:04:34.700 --> 00:04:38.700
And you can see that all the conventions that we created in our Markdown document, hyperlinks,

00:04:38.700 --> 00:04:45.100
bold, any commands that we executed, the output of those commands, even any equations or footnotes

00:04:45.100 --> 00:04:51.859
with hyperlinks, are all produced tables and even graphical output from your R code.

00:04:51.859 --> 00:04:57.179
So it's a really powerful tool just to create HTML files, but that was primarily how the

00:04:57.179 --> 00:05:01.859
old version was used.

00:05:01.859 --> 00:05:05.940
But now, as of the latest overhaul, we actually have a variety of different formats that you

00:05:05.940 --> 00:05:09.579
can very easily get into, including Microsoft Word.

00:05:09.579 --> 00:05:13.420
And so I can show a couple of examples here.

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:21.420
Okay, so knitting to PDF, again, has been possible before, but just to show you that

00:05:21.420 --> 00:05:26.420
it works, again, you get the equations formatted as you'd expect, you get footnotes, you get

00:05:26.420 --> 00:05:31.420
tables, all the things that we were seeing previously, you get in PDF as well.

00:05:31.420 --> 00:05:36.920
But then even more impressive is that all these things actually work in Microsoft Word

00:05:36.920 --> 00:05:37.920
as well.

00:05:37.920 --> 00:05:43.920
And so if you are fortunate or unfortunate enough, depending on your perspective, to

00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:50.040
need to work with Microsoft Word, then you can easily now create documents while working

00:05:50.040 --> 00:05:57.359
with tools that are a little more streamlined and efficient, but ultimately produce documents

00:05:57.359 --> 00:06:02.200
that you can share with other collaborators who may want to use Microsoft Word.

00:06:02.200 --> 00:06:05.519
And again, as you can see, all of the conventions that we've been using actually work.

00:06:05.519 --> 00:06:09.519
There's an editable Microsoft Word equation in here that represents the equation that

00:06:09.519 --> 00:06:10.519
you produce.

00:06:10.519 --> 00:06:14.320
Again, you have your input, your output, your images, tables that you can actually go in

00:06:14.320 --> 00:06:17.519
and edit and resize and do things that you want to do with.

00:06:17.519 --> 00:06:22.519
All right, so many of the output formats are already defined, so we've shown you that you

00:06:22.519 --> 00:06:27.519
can do Microsoft Word, you can do HTML, you can do LaTeX or PDF, but you can also, the

00:06:27.519 --> 00:06:31.920
entire system is pluggable, meaning that you can actually define a custom format and render

00:06:31.920 --> 00:06:35.920
your output into that format if you so desire.

00:06:35.920 --> 00:06:38.920
I'll show you the documentation for that at the end.

00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:42.920
We're not going to actually go through that exercise just for the sake of time today.

00:06:42.920 --> 00:06:47.920
But what's interesting about this is that you can create output formats that are entirely

00:06:47.920 --> 00:06:48.920
novel.

00:06:48.920 --> 00:06:52.920
So if HTML or Word or PDF aren't cutting it for you, you can actually create entirely

00:06:52.920 --> 00:06:55.920
new output formats or just modify existing formats.

00:06:56.920 --> 00:07:00.920
So for instance, if you are happy with HTML, but you want your company's CSS style sheet

00:07:00.920 --> 00:07:04.920
applied to it or something of that sort, then we can certainly do that.

00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:10.920
So I'll show you just an example, again, not of creating the element, but perhaps if your

00:07:10.920 --> 00:07:15.920
company had certain CSS styling that you wanted or a certain image header or something like

00:07:15.920 --> 00:07:20.920
that, perhaps you have a certain scaffolding that you want to provide around all the documents

00:07:20.920 --> 00:07:23.920
that you produce, we can certainly do that.

00:07:24.920 --> 00:07:28.920
So just as an example, I've created a new output format.

00:07:28.920 --> 00:07:34.920
So when I go to R Markdown, or rather an output template, when I go to R Markdown from template,

00:07:34.920 --> 00:07:37.920
you can see that I've created this package, Jeff package, and it has a new template within

00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:38.920
it.

00:07:38.920 --> 00:07:43.920
So you can imagine that your company could invest one time in producing these artifacts

00:07:43.920 --> 00:07:48.920
and then allow other users to share them within the convenience of R Markdown.

00:07:48.920 --> 00:07:52.920
So this is the template that I defined in my template.

00:07:52.920 --> 00:07:56.920
And you can see, perhaps you always need to end your documents with an inclusion in this

00:07:56.920 --> 00:08:00.920
company, or if you had a certain journal that you were submitting to and they had certain

00:08:00.920 --> 00:08:04.920
style guides for what sections you should provide, you can do that.

00:08:04.920 --> 00:08:08.920
But what's neat about this is that within my template, I've specified that there's a

00:08:08.920 --> 00:08:11.920
certain CSS style sheet that I want to be applied.

00:08:11.920 --> 00:08:15.920
And you can see this does not look like the original HTML document that I produced, but

00:08:15.920 --> 00:08:18.920
rather it has different colors and different fonts and things like that.

00:08:18.920 --> 00:08:25.920
So you can imagine that this could be styled for your company or your personal use if you

00:08:25.920 --> 00:08:27.920
prefer a different styling.

00:08:27.920 --> 00:08:28.920
So that's very easy to do.

00:08:28.920 --> 00:08:32.919
And again, I'll give you the link at the very end that shows you how you would go about

00:08:32.919 --> 00:08:35.919
creating your own.

00:08:35.919 --> 00:08:38.919
And then also you have custom formats.

00:08:38.919 --> 00:08:41.919
And so again, that's a little bit outside of the scope of what we're going to cover

00:08:41.919 --> 00:08:46.919
today, but I'll just show you a couple examples of ones that we've already produced.

00:08:46.919 --> 00:08:54.919
So if you've worked with Beamer, which is a LaTeX presentation format, that's historically

00:08:54.919 --> 00:08:57.919
been kind of difficult because you have to write the LaTeX by hand.

00:08:57.919 --> 00:09:00.919
What's great about this is that R Markdown, since it can render LaTeX, it can actually

00:09:00.919 --> 00:09:04.919
render Beamer as well once we've defined the Beamer template, which we've already done

00:09:04.919 --> 00:09:06.919
for you.

00:09:06.919 --> 00:09:08.919
And again, this is full-fledged R Markdown.

00:09:08.919 --> 00:09:12.919
So you can embed R codes, you can embed images, you can do all the things that you're used

00:09:12.919 --> 00:09:13.919
to doing in R Markdown.

00:09:13.919 --> 00:09:20.919
And then at the end, go to native PDF and you get this Beamer document that has all

00:09:20.919 --> 00:09:23.919
the content that you were expecting in it.

00:09:23.919 --> 00:09:29.919
But without having to go through the headache of learning LaTeX or even if you know it,

00:09:29.919 --> 00:09:30.919
sometimes using it can be a bit painful.

00:09:30.919 --> 00:09:36.919
And so this allows you just to continue working with R Markdown, a very convenient and efficient

00:09:36.919 --> 00:09:43.919
and streamlined format, but you can produce very rich and complex output formats.

00:09:43.919 --> 00:09:46.919
And then also we have different HTML slide templates.

00:09:46.919 --> 00:09:47.919
All right.

00:09:47.919 --> 00:09:51.919
And then kind of as the last example here, you can really go all the way with this and

00:09:51.919 --> 00:09:56.919
create entire templates that really define the entire structure of what you want to do.

00:09:56.919 --> 00:10:01.919
So you may have peeked at this when I was showing the previous template, but if you

00:10:01.919 --> 00:10:06.919
are submitting to JSS or you're submitting to UseR or something of that sort, then you

00:10:06.919 --> 00:10:11.919
can really, you know, you can define a template that you can continue to reuse.

00:10:11.919 --> 00:10:15.919
And so if you envision yourself submitting to a journal frequently or even if you're

00:10:15.919 --> 00:10:21.919
just submitting once, it may be worth the time to create this output template for you.

00:10:21.919 --> 00:10:25.919
So again, this is a UseR submission template.

00:10:25.919 --> 00:10:29.919
And you can see that we have, you know, all the basic R Markdown stuff that we've been

00:10:29.919 --> 00:10:30.919
using up until now.

00:10:30.919 --> 00:10:35.919
But what's interesting now is that we've actually, we're using a bibliography now as well.

00:10:35.919 --> 00:10:40.919
And by providing this references section, that's going to encapsulate all of the references

00:10:40.919 --> 00:10:42.919
that we've defined here.

00:10:42.919 --> 00:10:47.919
And we're using, in this case, we're just using a BibTeX format, but it actually supports

00:10:47.919 --> 00:10:50.919
a wide variety of different bibliography formats that you can use.

00:10:50.919 --> 00:10:52.919
So, but we'll just show you this example here.

00:10:52.919 --> 00:10:57.919
So if I go to knit, I'm going to get a PDF of my UseR submission.

00:10:57.919 --> 00:11:00.919
And you can see that it actually populates the bibliographies for me.

00:11:00.919 --> 00:11:01.919
It populates the citations.

00:11:01.919 --> 00:11:05.919
It does all these things that I would want it to do.

00:11:05.919 --> 00:11:08.919
And so if you're submitting to UseR, this is a very easy way to do it.

00:11:08.919 --> 00:11:12.919
But also if you're submitting to some journal that has certain conventions, you know, or

00:11:12.919 --> 00:11:17.919
a certain LaTeX style sheet or something like that, this is now a much easier way to interact

00:11:17.919 --> 00:11:21.919
with them.

00:11:21.919 --> 00:11:22.919
Okay.

00:11:22.919 --> 00:11:25.919
And then the last point here, just to make this kind of a teaser, I won't go into a whole

00:11:25.919 --> 00:11:30.919
lot of detail on this, but is that now when you're using the HTML format, you can actually

00:11:30.919 --> 00:11:31.919
support interactivity.

00:11:31.919 --> 00:11:35.919
So if you're familiar with the Shiny package that allows you to do kind of interactive

00:11:35.919 --> 00:11:42.919
web analysis within R, if I go to R Markdown and I click Shiny, I can create a Shiny document

00:11:42.919 --> 00:11:43.919
or a Shiny presentation.

00:11:43.919 --> 00:11:47.919
We'll just do a Shiny document for now, but Shiny presentations are actually kind of fun

00:11:47.919 --> 00:11:53.919
because you can imagine that you're using an HTML style or an HTML slideshow, but in

00:11:53.919 --> 00:11:56.919
the middle of your presentation, you have some interactive element that you can go in

00:11:56.919 --> 00:12:01.919
and kind of dig into in the middle of your presentation, which is kind of a fun thing

00:12:01.919 --> 00:12:03.919
to be able to do.

00:12:03.919 --> 00:12:07.919
So you can see here that this is just an R Markdown document, but if you're familiar

00:12:07.919 --> 00:12:10.919
with Shiny, you'll recognize some of these functions here.

00:12:10.919 --> 00:12:12.919
It's a very easy way to get into Shiny.

00:12:12.919 --> 00:12:15.919
There's really no overhead or boilerplate that's required.

00:12:15.919 --> 00:12:21.919
But when I go to run this document, I'll save it first, and when I go to run this document,

00:12:21.919 --> 00:12:25.919
you'll see that it's a regular R Markdown document just like we've seen before, but

00:12:25.919 --> 00:12:27.919
now it also has Shiny interactive components.

00:12:27.919 --> 00:12:35.919
And so when I go through and I toggle these different widgets that I can play with, I'm

00:12:35.919 --> 00:12:39.919
able to change all these things interactively within my R Markdown document.

00:12:39.919 --> 00:12:43.919
So this is a really great way if you kind of envision that you're creating a largely

00:12:43.919 --> 00:12:47.919
static document, but there are little pieces where you want to add some interactivity,

00:12:47.919 --> 00:12:51.919
then this is a really nice way to be able to do that.

00:12:56.919 --> 00:13:00.919
So finally here are a couple of resources, and we'll make these slides and everything

00:13:00.919 --> 00:13:07.919
else available to you online afterwards, but this would be the best resource for R Markdown

00:13:07.919 --> 00:13:09.919
here is rmarkdown.rstudio.com.

00:13:09.919 --> 00:13:13.919
That will have all the details that you need about creating custom templates, custom formats,

00:13:13.919 --> 00:13:18.919
anything that you'd want to create, and then the slides from today are actually available

00:13:18.919 --> 00:13:20.919
here as well.

00:13:20.919 --> 00:13:24.919
The one trick here is that you'll probably want to download the latest version of RStudio,

00:13:24.919 --> 00:13:28.919
so just for your convenience to make it easier to use all these things.

00:13:28.919 --> 00:13:33.919
Now, again, if I didn't mention this before, R Markdown is an open source freely available

00:13:33.919 --> 00:13:34.919
R package.

00:13:34.919 --> 00:13:39.919
It's downloadable from CRAN, and so you're certainly welcome to use this from any R editing

00:13:39.919 --> 00:13:40.919
environment that you choose.

00:13:40.919 --> 00:13:45.919
It's just that in RStudio, we've done the work to make some of these things a little

